# define a function to define the sentiment analysis result 
def senan(c):
    if c>0:
        a = "pos"
    elif c<0:
        a = "neg"
    else:
        a ="neu"
    return a
In [4]:
# use sentiment analysis processing data
Sid = sid()
df['scores'] = df['sentence_spacy'].apply(lambda sentence_spacy: Sid.polarity_scores(sentence_spacy))
df['compound'] = df['scores'].apply(lambda score_dict: score_dict['compound'])
df['comp_score'] = df['compound'].apply(senan)
df

Among Authors¶

In [5]:
# extract authors name
authors = pd.Series(df['author']).unique()

# plot a bar graph with authors and sentment analysis result
df2=pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((36, 3),int),index=pd.Series(df['author']).unique(),columns=pd.Index(['pos', 'neg',"neu"]))
for senti in ["pos", 'neg',"neu"]:
    for name in authors:
        tempdf = df[df['comp_score']==senti]
        tempdf = tempdf[tempdf["author"]==name]
        num = len(tempdf)
        df2[senti][name]=num 
        
df2.plot.bar()

In [10]:
# define wordcloud plot function
def plot_wordcloud(text,title):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white",
                        stopwords = set(STOPWORDS),
                        max_words = 100,
                         max_font_size = 40,
                         relative_scaling = 1,
                         random_state = 3
    ).generate(str(text))
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
In [11]:
# plot wordcloud for continental authors
for i in cont:
    could_0 = df.loc[df['author'] == i]['sentence_lowered']
    plot_wordcloud(could_0,i)
plt.show()

We can see that most of the words show in wordcloud are neutral, and some of them can be either positive or negative, regarding the context of the article. However, I notice that some words seems to be "mis-analysis", such as "ri", "o" in Foucault wordcloud. Then I found the sentence with "ri":

"Mor ri's Grand dictionnaire historique of."

I translated this sentence with Google translate and I get the following sentence in English:

"Morri's Great Historical Dictionary of."

Hence, we can see the previous sentence is written in French, then translated or quoted by the authors. So I search about Foucault, whose full name is Paul-Michel Foucault, a French philosopher, historian of ideas, writer, political activist, and literary critic. Then, a question raised in my mind: why would this book includes two languages? So, I search about the book and found the answer: This is the reference which quoted by the authors. Similar things happened on other two continental authors.

I want to see if this happens in other schools, so I pick another two schools, nietzsche and feminism, to see their word clouds. I assume I will find more "positive" words regarding they both have more positive sentment sentenses. Here are the results:

# plot wordcloud for authors in nietzsche school and in feminism school

As shown in the data description above, only Nietzche belongs to the school Nietzsche, and the other three authors belong to the school feminism.

We can still see some noise data listed in the wordcloud. For example, "t", "w", "ye", and"inh" listed in Wollstonecraft's wordcloud. So we can say that references generate data noise to analysis in our datasets. We can remove the references as a step to cleaning data next time to reduce the data noise.

Furthermore, I found something interesting with these four new wordclouds. If we just look at the wordclouds for these four authors, we might conclude that Nietzsche would be similar to feminism, because Nietzsche mentioned "men" and "children" often, just like Beauvoir mentioned "man" a lot.

Moreover, there is a word, dtype, appears in five wordclouds. It seems to be a terminology used in philosophy area. Hence, I tried to search this word up among "sentence_lowered", but I found nothing. I would consider this word is also a data noise.

Last but not least, though Davis is one of the feminism philosophers,but it seems like what she was sharing is diferent from other two authors, as she sldom mentioned sex, like "men" and "wemen", in her articles. We can deep further to see what's her points of view in the real world, compared to other two authors.

Compare what we get to the real world¶

To analyze further, we meed to search up the real world situation, compared to what we get from sentiment analysis and wordcloud, to see if we get a correct understanding of the data.

Let's first see: is it reasonable that the attitude of continental authors tends to be neutral? I would say yes, according to Continental philosophy is a set of 19th- and 20th-century philosophical traditions from mainland Europe. During that period, people having different thoughts, either the time in world wars or the time in cold war. Also, it contains different schools so that it is possible to attack or defense for their schools as well. As a result, it makes sense the sentences wrtitten by continental philosophers are more neutral than other schools.

We move little further and detailed, to see if Nietzche school is similar to feminism school. However, it is not. Nietzsche's philosophy contemplates the meaning of values and their significance to human existence. This means not only for women, Nietzsche's insight is for all human beings. This is no surprised why there are also so much "children" is listed in Nietzsche's wordcloud. Also, he mentioned the most about "suffering", and we can tell he might talk much about how to make people suffer less and what they were suffering.

Last but not least, we can also tell the difference between Davis and other feminism authors. Unlike Simone de Beauvoir and Mary Wollstonecraft, Angela Davis actived in a stage African-American Civil Rights Movement. In this context, it is no wonder her words tend to be more aggressive, such as "raged" and "slavery".

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, utilizing sentiment analysis, we can actually see the authors attitude and we can also guess about the era they were living. Also, we can tell what was going on based on the words authors used differently in diferent schools. Most importantly, we can use wordcloud to see the goal of the authors, and finally understand their school's goal.
